Astra, Bukit Asam, Jasa Marga, Telkom: Indonesia Equity Preview

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-10-06T01:57:12Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-06/astra-bukit-asam-jasa-marga-telkom-indonesia-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies may
have unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and share prices are as of the previous close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  rose 0.7 percent to 3,293.24.  Energy companies: Crude oil futures jumped 5.3 percent to
$79.68 a barrel in  New York  yesterday, the most in almost five
months. Oil was last traded at $79.65 a barrel.  PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC IJ), Indonesia’s
largest listed oil company, slid 1.1 percent to 1,880 rupiah and
PT Energi Mega Persada (ENRG IJ), the second biggest, gained 1.8
percent to 116 rupiah.  PT Astra Agro Lestari (AALI IJ): The company’s January to
September crude palm oil output gained 20 percent from a year
earlier to 930,827 metric tons, it said. Astra Agro, Indonesia’s
largest listed plantation company by market value, slipped 0.3
percent to 16,950 rupiah.  PT Astra International (ASII IJ):  Indonesia ’s biggest
automotive retailer plans to spend $1.5 billion next year to
expand the business, Kontan reported, citing Director Gunawan
Geniusahardja. Astra will use 40 percent of that total for
infrastructure projects, the report said. The stock slid 2.4
percent to 57,300 rupiah.  PT Jasa Marga (JSMR IJ): Indonesia’s largest toll-road
operator expects to complete a 10-kilometer highway on the
resort island of Bali before a meeting of Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation members in 2013, Finance Director Reynaldi
Hermansjah told reporters at an event in Jakarta. Jasa Marga
climbed 1.4 percent to 3,700 rupiah.  PT Tambang Batubara Bukit Asam (PTBA IJ): The Indonesian
state-owned coal producer aims to increase its production to 50
million tons by 2015, President Director Sukrisno told investors
in Jakarta. Bukit Asam fell 3.1 percent to 13,950 rupiah.  PT Telekomunikasi Indonesia (TLKM IJ): Indonesia’s biggest
telephone company canceled a plan to buy a stake in  Cambodia ’s
CamGSM Ltd., Sudiro Asno, finance director at Telekomunikasi,
said. Telekomunikasi said in April it planned to buy a 51
percent stake in CamGSM. Telkom, as the company is known,
advanced 3.4 percent to 7,700 rupiah.  PT  Total Bangun Persada (TOTL)  : The construction company
posted revenue for the nine months ended Sept. 30 of 1.2
trillion rupiah ($134 million),  Bisnis Indonesia  reported,
citing Director Moeljati Soetrisno. Total rose 2.3 percent to
220 rupiah.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at   dboey@bloomberg.net  